`,qe(t.p,{children:"Real-world multimodal emotion recognition often faces two practical challenges: cross-modal conflict and missing modalities. However, many existing datasets only provide a single multimodal label and assume that all modalities are always available, which makes these settings difficult to study systematically. To address this, we introduce EmoMM, a benchmark designed for multimodal emotion recognition under both modality conflict and modality missingness. EmoMM provides both unimodal and multimodal emotion annotations, enabling evaluation under full-modality and missing-modality conditions."}),`
